    "content": "The experimental results demonstrate a dramatic performance difference among the three heuristic functions. Manhattan distance proved to be the most efficient, expanding only 40.0 nodes on average with a search time of 0.151 ms. Euclidean distance expanded 153.7 nodes (3.8 times more than Manhattan), while diagonal distance expanded 244.1 nodes (6.1 times more than Manhattan). These findings strongly support the theoretical principle that admissible heuristics with higher consistency values significantly reduce the search space exploration. The Manhattan distance's superior performance on grid-based environments confirms its suitability for this class of pathfinding problems."
