  {
    "line": 19,
    "content": "The superiority of Manhattan distance in grid-based pathfinding can be explained through the concept of heuristic consistency. A heuristic $h(n)$ is consistent if for every node $n$ and its successor $n'$, the inequality $h(n) \\leq c(n,n') + h(n')$ holds, where $c(n,n')$ is the cost of moving from $n$ to $n'$. Manhattan distance satisfies this property more strictly than Euclidean or diagonal distance in grid environments with eight-directional movement."
